Hi all,

Bradley M. Kuhn wrote:
>> On Sun, Jan 11, 2009 at 06:43:56PM +1000, antispam box wrote:
>>> Good day.
>>>
>>> I see the last update of ddccontrol was made in 2006 year. Has
>>> this project the active developers now?
> 
> Roberto S√°nchez replied at 19:47 (EST) on Sunday:
> 
>> Not really.  The original developers are no longer working on the
>> project.  At one point, I was interested in taking over, however I no
>> longer have that interest and I have turned my attention to other
>> things.  I still subscribe to the mailing list so that I can help out
>> when I can with user problems (which are not numerous).  If you are
>> interested in taking over, let me know.

I was originally maintaining this project, however, it seems that
nowadays it's more about updating a database and nothing else, so I lost
interest in it. Furthermore I use a laptop now and have no use for
ddccontrol anymore.

I should probably do a release a new version that doesn't ask people to
send their monitor information unless they created the xml file
themselves...

> I think the challenge in taking this project over relates to
> understanding how the video cards work and how to use the i2c and other
> interfaces.  I posted earlier about a challenge I am having -- using the
> ddccontrol to handle an LVDS display on a laptop.  I spent a few hours
> reviewing the code, but the low-level nature of the programming seems to
> indicate you need an understanding at a low hardware level.

The first question I would ask myself if I were you is to know whether
your LVDS display is having a i2c bus (I guess so since these displays
usually give back EEPROM information about their resolution and so on).
The next question is to know whether the display is supporting DDC/CI or
another control protocol. Also, if there are no tools for Windows, I
think it is rather likely to mean there is no such interface...

> There is not a lot of tutorial information about this type of
> programming online (at least that I can find).

It's basically kernel code copied in userspace. Don't expect tutorials
for that, the code varies according to specifications of the graphics
card, and that information is proprietary.

> One thing I'd suggest,
> Roberto, if you have time, write up a 100 line tutorial on how to learn
> how to maintain the project.  It might have a greater chance of getting
> someone to take over.

It would probably be my job to do that... But I guess that if someone
with enough time and motivation, and relevant skills, wants to take
over, it should be feasible... However don't expect support from me, as
I'm quite busy with other things (I think you've seen that Roberto .-)).

Best regards,

Nicolas


